9.body: This chapter is a GNU make crash course. It will explain how to create a build system for almost any C/C++ project. GNU make works by specifying targets. These targets 'produce' a file from a set of arguments - for example: %.o: %.c gcc -c $< -o $@ %.o specifies a file with the .o extension. %.c specifies a file with the same name, but a .c extension. $< is the first argument (in this case %.c) and %@ is the target (%.o). In other words, this target means 'to create a file X.o, we need X.c, and to run gcc -c X.c -o X.o' The -c flag in gcc tells it to output an object file (.o) and -o tells it the name of the file to output. Another important concept in GNU make is variables.
